Good move 👍 — restarting is actually the right call at this stage.

Now let’s make sure you bring the cluster back correctly, otherwise it can fall back into the same standby loop.


---

🚨 What to do AFTER reboot

✅ Step 1: Check which node came up first

On both controllers, run:

sm-dump | grep controller-services

👉 You want ONE node like this:

controller-services active active ✅

👉 And the other:

standby standby


---

🔴 If BOTH are still standby (very important)

👉 Then you MUST force election again:

On controller-1:

sudo systemctl stop sm

On controller-0:

sudo systemctl restart sm


---

✅ Step 2: Verify core services on ACTIVE node

On the ACTIVE controller:

sm-dump | egrep "postgres|keystone|sysinv"

👉 Expected:

enabled-active enabled-active


---

✅ Step 3: Check Ceph (critical)

sm-dump | grep ceph-mon

👉 Should be:

enabled-active enabled-active

If not → we fix Ceph next.


---

✅ Step 4: Test CLI

sudo -E bash -c "source /etc/platform/openrc && system host-list"


---

⚠️ Very Important

After reboot:

Sometimes both controllers try standby

System waits forever → no recovery


👉 That’s why forcing one node (step above) is key


---

🧠 What success looks like

Component	Expected

controller-services	active/active
postgres	active
keystone	active
ceph-mon	active
system host-list	working



